Task Name: Add feature 12 hrs time limit for cookie
Task Content:
Normal window:-
When we accept/reject the cookie, It will not showing the pop-up window again for 12 hrs. 
Once we accept/reject the cookie then close the tab and again open the site in new tab, the pop-up window is not showing for 12hrs because we store the accept/reject cookie time for this particular brower.
Once we accept/reject the cookie and then we close the complete window and open the site again, the pop-up window is not showing for 12hrs because we store the accept/reject cookie time for this particular brower.
Incognito mode:-
When we accept/reject the cookie, It will not showing whereever the brower window or tab not close.
Once we accept/reject the cookie then close the tab or window and open again the site then it will show the pop-up window again because this mode can't store the cookies.

Task Name: recipes and blog detail page front end design
Add feature 12 hrs time limit for cookie
Task Content:
Normal window:-
When we accept/reject the cookie, It will not showing the pop-up window again for 12 hrs. 
Once we accept/reject the cookie then close the tab and again open the site in new tab, the pop-up window is not showing for 12hrs because we store the accept/reject cookie time for this particular brower.
Once we accept/reject the cookie and then we close the complete window and open the site again, the pop-up window is not showing for 12hrs because we store the accept/reject cookie time for this particular brower.
Incognito mode:-
When we accept/reject the cookie, It will not showing whereever the brower window or tab not close.
Once we accept/reject the cookie then close the tab or window and open again the site then it will show the pop-up window again because this mode can't store the cookies.

","by":"sindhuja.nelaturu@bizcredence.com","assigned":false,"date":"5/14/2025, 7:05:14 PM GMT+5:30","resolved":"N/A"},{"text":"Response  given- Requirement 1: Wishlist Stock Hold and Notification Logic

User Story Extract:
“Users should be able to add multiple instances of the same product to their wishlist. A notification message should be displayed as per business direction: ‘The item will be held for 45 minutes / 1 hour.’”
Clarification & Aligned Responses:
Is the wishlist intended to function like a reservation queue, meaning the stock is blocked for the user during the 45 minutes/1 hour hold period?
Response:- Yes, the wishlist in this case is designed to function as a temporary reservation mechanism. Upon addition to the wishlist, the item is held in the inventory system, effectively reserving stock across all active omnichannel channels for a defined duration.

Could you please confirm whether the hold duration is 45 minutes or 1 hour, as both are currently mentioned?
Response:- Confirmed. The defined hold duration is 45 minutes, as per the latest BRD and business decision.

Does the hold period apply per instance added to the wishlist, or is it applicable to the entire SKU irrespective of quantity?
Response:- The hold period applies at the SKU level, per user wishlist. The quantity logic follows a first-hold-first-release protocol, applicable regardless of whether multiple instances are added.

Is the system expected to automatically remove the item from the wishlist once the hold period expires?
Response:- Yes. Once the 45-minute hold window elapses, the system will automatically release the reserved inventory and remove the item from the wishlist, unless manually acted upon (e.g., added to cart or explicitly removed).

Should this behavior apply uniformly to all users (guest, registered and logged-in, registered but not logged-in)?
Response:- Yes. The behavior is uniform across all user types, including guests, registered (logged-in or not). Session-based storage and email/phone cookie mapping will ensure temporary user-specific hold logic applies consistently.
---Requirement 2: Terms and Conditions Acceptance Logic
User Story Extract:*“The Terms and Conditions checkbox behavior should be refined:
1) Registered users should only be prompted to accept updated T&Cs, not on every purchase.
2) Guest users should be prompted to accept T&Cs with every purchase attempt.”*
Clarification & Aligned Responses:
Should all users be prompted to accept updated T&Cs?Response:-  Yes. All users — registered or guest — will be prompted to accept the T&Cs whenever a newer version is released, as per BRD guidelines. Guest users will also need to accept the T&Cs for every purchase attempt, in line with transient session behavior and legal compliance.
Is the T&C acceptance expected to be stored at the account level for registered users?Response:-  Yes. For registered users, the system logs T&C acceptance at the account level, recording version ID, timestamp, and user ID. This ensures historical traceability and aligns with compliance requirements.
How is versioning or change detection of the T&Cs planned to be managed?
Response:-  A centralized versioning mechanism is already defined in the BRD. Each T&C document has a unique version ID, content hash, and publish timestamp, stored in the document repository. The system compares the user’s last accepted version with the current active version to trigger re-acceptance workflows.
